Spectra-Physics InSight-X3

This software was developed to allow for the control of the major Spectra-Physics Insight X3 femtosecond laser parameters from custom software. Designed as the MC module, it can be started as an independent program, including in a compiled form, and integrated in a larger GUI assembly. In both cases, it can be a part of the MC communication assembly, and be controlled from other programs of the assembly, including the Sequence Runner (SR), via the ZeroMQ channel (if this module is a part of an MC assembly of programs written in the same language, e.g., LabView, it can also use MC channels of this language).

Only one program at a time can control the laser. And so, apart from being useful for controlling the laser from custom software, this program is a fully fledged package, capable of doing most things that the software supplied by the manufacturer can do. Moreover, when the laser is connected by a long USB cable, we found this software to maintain a more stable connection than the one from the manufacturer.

Compiled program:
Main Window Setup window Serial comm program

Main Window

  • The power button shows whether the laser is turned on. If it's OFF, press the button for at least 3 seconds to turn it on.
  • When the laser if turned ON, there is still no output until a shutter is opened. There are two shutters in the laser, one for the tunable IR output, and another for a high power (over 4W) 1045nm beam. To open either, press on the corresponding button for over 3 seconds.
  • The wavelength, nm control allows changing the wavelength within the allowed nanometer range.
  • Power out, W shows the tunable output. Notice that the Fixed IR output power has to be measured manually, and doesn't depend on the selected operational wavelength.
  • The series of the colored circle indicators quickly summarizes the current state of the laser. Hover mouse over each of them to see what they mean.
    • green: #fix
    • blue: #fix
    • red: #fix
  • Comm history panel displays most recent communication with the laser
  • error indicator turns red if there is an error in operation of the program (not the laser).
  • Extra button opens the Setup window shown above.
  • Stop stops the program (#fix ?switching the laser into standby mode?). Make sure the serial communication program is stopped as well.

Setup window

The setup window let's you set up the port settings for communication with the laser, connect to the laser using these settings, as well as to send a series of pre-defined commands to the laser (the responses are to be read in the Comm history window in the main window). The available commands are extracted from the commands filepath control. In this version of the software, the commands aren't explained. For their meaning, see the laser manual below.

Serial communication program

The communication with the laser in the program is implemented over the via an asynchronously running program (which is probably the reason for a relatively higher stability of the program to dropping communication with laser when operated over a long USB cable compared to the one supplied by the manufacturer). There is nothing to be done with this window, except that it has to be running for normal operation, and when one wants to close the laser control program, this serial communication has to be stopped as well.

Notice that in the upcoming version of the laser control program, serial communication program will moved to a subpanel in the main program.
